nd":"Widdington, Essex, England"},"en":{"1374–1437":"1374–1437","1370–1431":"1370–1431","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","1410–1466":"1410–1466","1325–1376":"1325–1376","–1448":"–1448","1437":"1437","1448":"1448","about 1390":"about 1390","1325":"1325","1400":"1400","1466":"1466","1410":"1410","1376":"1376","1431":"1431","1374":"1374","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Fitche Castle, Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Bocking, Essex, England":"Bocking, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Widdington, Essex, England":"Widdington, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Worth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Worth, for example in Cheshire, Dorset, Sussex, and Kent, from Old English <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. The vocabulary word probably survived into the Middle English period in the sense of a subsidiary settlement dependent on a main village, and in some cases the surname may be a topographic name derived from this use. Compare   Worthy  .","North German: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>wort</i> ‘enclosure, elevated piece of land, farmstead’, or a habitational name from a place so named in northern Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Word","meanings":["Perhaps an Americanized form of Dutch <b>Van der Woord</b>, a habitational name from any of the places called Woord or Woerd.","English: variant of   Worth  ."]},{"name":"Wortmann","meanings":["North German: topographic name for someone who lived on a raised, secure site, Middle Low German <i>wort</i> + <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Worth   2."]},{"name":"Worthy","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>worthi</i> ‘enclosure’ (Old English <i>worthig</i>, <i>weorthig</i>, <i>wurthig</i>). The surname is probably habitational, from a place so named, such as Worthy (Hampshire, Devon) and Worthy Hill Farm (Wiltshire)."]},{"name":"Wurdeman","meanings":["Americanized form of North German <b>Wurdemann</b>, also <b>Würdemann</b>: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>wurt</i> ‘farm area, field, woodland’. Compare   Worth  .","Americanized form of German <b>Würdemann</b>: from an ancient Germanic personal name formed with Old High German <i>wirdi</i> ‘dignity’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’."]},{"name":"Wirth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Gunter, Dieter, Ernst, Gerhard, Manfred, Reinhold, Armin, Erna.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): occupational name for an inn-keeper, Middle High German <i>wirt</i>, German <i>Wirt</i>.","German: status name for a man who was head of a family and master of his own household, from the same word in the sense ‘provider’."]}]},{"name":"Cora","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Name apparently coined by  James Fenimore Cooper  for one of the characters in The Last of the Mohicans (  1826 ). It could represent a Latinized form of Greek <i>Korē</i> ‘maiden’. In classical mythology this was a euphemistic name of the goddess of the underworld, Persephone, and would not have been a well-omened name to take. Nevertheless, this has not proved an obstacle to its use in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":8,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Cora Worth was born in 1374, in Bocking, Essex, England as the daughter of Abram Worth and Mrs Abram Worth. She married Thomas Fitch about 1390, in Essex, England. They were the 